04670nam a22006975i 9780814724477DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147244777 a10.18574/97808147244772doi  a(DE-B1597)548057  a(OCoLC)1175629380  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE185.97.R27bR46 2016 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a323.0922231 aKersten, Andrew E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReframing Randolph :bLabor, Black Freedom, and the Legacies of A. Philip Randolph /cAndrew E. Kersten, Clarence Lang. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture, Labor, History ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- t1 A Reintroduction to Asa Philip Randolph -- t2 Researching Randolph -- t3 A. Philip Randolph -- t4 Keeping His Faith -- t5 Brotherhood Men and Singing Slackers -- t6 "The Spirit and Strategy of the United Front" -- t7 Organizing Gender -- t8 Beyond A. Philip Randolph -- t9 The "Void at the Center of the Story" -- t10 No Exit -- tSelect Bibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAtone time, Asa Philip Randolph (1889-1979) was a household name. As president ofthe all-black Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP), he was an embodimentof America's multifaceted radical tradition, a leading spokesman for BlackAmerica, and a potent symbol of trade unionism and civil rights agitation fornearly half a century. But with the dissolution of the BSCP in the 1970s, theassaults waged against organized labor in the 1980s, and the overall silencingof labor history in U.S. popular discourse, he has been largely forgotten amonglarge segments of the general public before whom he once loomed so large.Historians, however, have not only continued to focus on Randolph himself, buthis role (either direct, or via his legacy) in a wide range of social,political, cultural, and even religious milieu and movements. The authors of Reframing Randolph have taken Randolph's dusty portrait down fromthe wall to reexamine and reframe it, allowing scholars to regard him in new,and often competing, lights. This collection of essays gathers, for the veryfirst time, many genres of perspectives on Randolph. Featuring both establishedand emergent intellectual voices, this project seeks to avoid both hagiographyand blanket condemnation alike. The contributors represent the diverse waysthat historians have approached the importance of his long and complex careerin the main political, social, and cultural currents of twentieth-centuryAfrican American specifically, and twentieth-century U.S. history overall. Thecentral goal of Reframing Randolph isto achieve a combination of synthetic and critical reappraisal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfrican American labor leadersvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights workerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aLang, Clarence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814724477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814724477.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK